The '''Warkworth Radio Astronomical Observatory''' is located just south of [[Warkworth, New Zealand]], off [[New Zealand State Highway 1|State Highway 1]], about 50&nbsp;km north of Auckland.  It is operated by the Institute for Radio Astronomy and Space Research, [[Auckland University of Technology]]. The [[Warkworth Radio Telescope|WARK12M 12m Radio Telescope]] was constructed in 2008. In 2010, a licence to operate the New Zealand Telecom 30m dish was granted, which led to the construction of the [[Warkworth 2 dish|WARK30M 30m Radio Telescope]]. First observations with the Australian Long Baseline Array took place in 2011.<ref>D., Dickey, 3 March 2011, Rodney Times,p.11, Warkworth in control as telescopes link up.A historic link-up of six Australian radio telescope sites with the Warkworth Radio Observatory could be the start of a very fast broadband speed.</ref>

A [[Hydrogen maser]] is installed on-site for very accurate time required by VLBI observations. The observatory has a 1Gbit/s connection to the [[Kiwi Advanced Research and Education Network]], providing high speed data transfers for files and e-VLBI.<ref>Weston, S., Natusch, T., Gulyaev, S., 2010, in Proceedings of
the 17th Electronics New Zealand Conference, submitted
(preprint astro-ph/1011.0227)</ref>

